<div style="text-align: right;"><div class="page-rate-widget-box"><span class="rate-points">rating:&nbsp;<span class="number prw54353">+243</span></span><span class="rateup btn btn-default"><a title="I like it" href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.modules.PageRateWidgetModule.listeners.rate(event, 1)">+</a></span><span class="ratedown btn btn-default"><a title="I don't like it" href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.modules.PageRateWidgetModule.listeners.rate(event, -1)">&#8211;</a></span><span class="cancel btn btn-default"><a title="Cancel my vote" href="javascript:;" onclick="WIKIDOT.modules.PageRateWidgetModule.listeners.cancelVote(event)">x</a></span></div></div>
<div class="image-container floatright"><img src="http://scp-wiki.wdfiles.com/local--files/k-class-complete-list/k-class2.png" width="305px" alt="k-class2.png" class="image" /></div>
<p>K-Class Scenarios are hypothetical situations that could have drastic effects on normality or reality, including the <em>end of the world</em>. The Foundation games out what can happen in these events, and authors on the wiki often reference these contingency plans&#8230; or times they have failed.</p>
<p>This collaborative page exists to document all K-Class Scenarios used on the wiki.</p>
<p><strong>Disclaimers</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>There is no canon definition for <em>any</em> K-Class Scenario. This page should <em>not</em> be seen as a &quot;canonical&quot; resource. Please do not hassle authors for &quot;misusing&quot; these scenarios.</li>
<li>This list is meant to be <em>descriptive</em>, not <em>prescriptive</em>. Definitions are based on usage in articles, not what anyone <em>thinks</em> they <em>should</em> mean. (For earlier lists with invented definitions, scroll down.)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>A bit on notation:</strong> (I treated any of these grammatical variants as equivalent.)</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<ul>
<li>Scenarios <em>generally</em> follow: &lt;Letter&gt;K-Class &lt;description/end-of-the-world&gt; scenario</li>
<li>&quot;K-class <em>scenario</em>&quot; and &quot;K-class <em>event</em>&quot; seem to be used interchangeably. There's no consistent logic to it. Scenario was used about 4 times as often as event in my initial search.</li>
<li>Capitalization (XK-Class End&#8230;, XK-class end&#8230;) and truncation (end-of-the-world, &quot;end of the world&quot;, end of the world) don't seem to have any set standard.</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<p><strong>Do you want to help?</strong><br />
Please do! This is a collaboration. See the steps below:</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;So&nbsp;you&nbsp;want&nbsp;to&nbsp;link&nbsp;an&nbsp;article?</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><strong>So you want to link an article?</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Please, please do this! My initial scraping only covered <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/system:page-tags/tag/k-class-scenario">tagged</a> SCPs, so tales and other articles need attention.</li>
<li>Make sure the article is staying in the positive ratings (remaining at +1 or above for 24 hours) before adding the link: it's a pain to go through and clean up afterwards.</li>
<li>If the article uses an existing prefix and fits a common definition, just add the link and update the count (# SCPs, # Tales, # Others). Maybe add the Alternative title if it's new and sounds cool.</li>
<li>If the scenario is inconsistent with others in that prefix, OR is the first article using a prefix, OR only appears in a -J, please add it to the appropriate table using this format:</li>
</ul>
<div class="code">
<pre>
<code>||~ Title ||~ Definition ||~ Articles ||
|| || || ||</code>
</pre></div>
<ul>
<li>If you need a whole tab, here is a basic format:</li>
</ul>
<div class="code">
<pre>
<code>[[tab prefix]]
**Most Common:** 
**Used in:** # SCPs, # Tales, # Other
**Primary definition:** 
**Alternative titles:** 
**SCPs:** 
**Tales and other articles:**

**Inconsistent Uses**
||~ Title ||~ Definition ||~ Articles ||
||  || || ||
[[/tab]]</code>
</pre></div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;So&nbsp;you&nbsp;want&nbsp;to&nbsp;add&nbsp;or&nbsp;update&nbsp;a&nbsp;definition?</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><strong>So you want to add or update a definition?</strong><br />
Maybe you were the author of a one-off or inconsistent-use scenario, or maybe you want to update a primary definition that is out of date. (Or, you know, if it could be better.) Go for it! Just remember:</p>
<ul>
<li>Definitions should be <em>usage</em>-based. Only create or update definitions to fit their use in articles.</li>
<li>If the usage and title is really different from its current prefix, consider adding it to &quot;Inconsistent Uses&quot;.</li>
<li>It helps if you add a note down in the &quot;Short description of changes:&quot; before you hit &quot;Save&quot;</li>
<li>Do not add definitions without a successful, linked article!</li>
</ul>
</div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
</div>
</div>
